{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 19:37:35.754945", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting diagnosis report\\nGoal: assess network health, identify anomalies, localize faulty device(s), and determine likely root cause(s). No remediation actions supplied.\\n\\nSummary / overall health\\n- The routed/core/server plane (10.200.0.0/24 — DNS, DHCP, web servers, load balancer) and OSPF routing appear healthy. Multiple infrastructure hosts and servers successfully pinged each other (reachability tests show almost all tested pairs status \"ok\" with 0% loss).\\n- A local, isolated outage affects one access host: host_1_1_1_1 (10.1.1.22). This host is not reachable at L3 (cannot reach its default gateway or the DHCP server), while L2 learning of its MAC is present on the access switch and the distribution router.\\n\\nWhat I tested / tools used\\n- get_reachability (overall reachability matrix)\\n- ping from host_1_1_1_1 -> 10.200.0.8 (dhcp_server)\\n- ip config / route / neighbor on host_1_1_1_1 (get_host_net_config, exec_shell)\\n- get_host_net_config on router_dist_1_1 and switch_access_1_1_1\\n- ip neigh and bridge FDB checks on router_dist_1_1 and switch_access_1_1_1\\n- ping from router_dist_1_1 -> host_1_1_1_1 and from another host -> 10.1.1.22\\n\\nKey observations / evidence\\n1) Host IP and routing (host_1_1_1_1)\\n- host_1_1_1_1 ifconfig/ip:\\n  - eth0: 10.1.1.22/24, default route: default via 10.1.1.1 dev eth0\\n  - resolv.conf: nameserver 10.200.0.2\\n- Host-to-server ping failed:\\n  - ping 10.200.0.8 from host_1_1_1_1 -> “Destination Host Unreachable” (100% loss).\\n- Host L2 neighbor for gateway:\\n  - ip neigh on host shows \"10.1.1.1 dev eth0 FAILED\" (host cannot resolve gateway MAC).\\n\\n2) Router / distribution view (router_dist_1_1)\\n- router_dist_1_1 bridge and route info:\\n  - br0 has 10.1.1.1/24; routes for 10.1.x.x and 10.200.0.0/24 present via OSPF.\\n- router_dist_1_1 neighbor table shows 10.1.1.22 dev br0 state FAILED.\\n- bridge FDB on router_dist_1_1 contains a MAC entry for the host:\\n  - c6:ac:f4:9b:df:b0 (host_1_1_1_1) present on eth1 master br0.\\n- Ping from router_dist_1_1 to 10.1.1.22 resulted in \"Destination Host Unreachable\" (ARP resolution failure).\\n\\n3) Access switch (switch_access_1_1_1)\\n- switch bridge FDB shows c6:ac:f4:9b:df:b0 (host_1_1_1_1) learned on eth1 (the host-facing port).\\n- switch ports and FDB otherwise look normal; other hosts on the same access switch and VLAN are reachable.\\n\\n4) Cross-checks\\n- Ping from another access host (host_1_1_1_2) to 10.1.1.22 also returned Destination Host Unreachable (reported by 10.1.1.23), consistent with router/distribution not being able to ARP-resolve 10.1.1.22.\\n- The rest of the access subnets and inter-router OSPF routes are present and functioning: DNS, DHCP, web servers and load balancer respond to pings from other parts of the network (see get_reachability results and router_core_1 routing table).\\n\\nLocalization (where the fault likely is)\\n- Problem is localized to the access host and/or the host’s interface/OS behavior:\\n  - Device: host_1_1_1_1 (10.1.1.22) — L3 unreachable.\\n  - Evidence places the issue at or just above L2: the access switch has learned the host’s MAC on the correct port (so physical link and basic L2 learning occurred), but L3 neighbor resolution (ARP) between the distribution router and the host is failing.\\n- Not likely a core/distribution routing or OSPF problem:\\n  - OSPF routes to the 10.1.1.0/24 network exist and other hosts in 10.1.1.0/24 are reachable.\\n  - The distribution router’s br0 and routes are present.\\n\\nLikely root cause(s) (hypotheses)\\n- Host is not responding to ARP requests (or ARP replies are not seen by the distribution router), producing a functional L3 outage for that IP:\\n  - Evidence: router_dist and the host both show the peer as \"FAILED\" in ip neigh; router cannot ARP-resolve the host; host shows gateway ARP FAILED. Yet the switch FDB still contains the host MAC (so the host did once transmit frames and the switch learned the MAC).\\n- Possible specific causes on host_1_1_1_1:\\n  - Host OS/network stack misconfiguration: ARP disabled, arp_ignore/arp_announce sysctl settings set to prevent ARP replies, or NOARP on interface.\\n  - Host firewall or security software blocking ARP replies or ICMP in a way that prevents L3 reachability. (Note: standard Linux iptables does not block ARP; specialized filtering or ebtables/arptables could.)\\n  - Host NIC driver/firmware problem leading to receive-side failures (host can send frames (so MAC learned) but is not responding to ARP requests).\\n  - Duplicate-IP situation (some other node briefly using same IP) causing ARP confusion — less likely because FDB MAC mapping matches host NIC and no other conflicting MAC/IP pair was observed.\\n  - Host in power-save, suspended network stack or otherwise transiently unresponsive after having sent traffic (e.g., it transmitted something, switch learned MAC, then host stopped responding).\\n- Less likely causes:\\n  - Access switch port physical failure: unlikely because MAC is present on switch, and other hosts on same switch are reachable.\\n  - Distribution router configuration error: unlikely because router has routes and communicates with many other hosts in that subnet and the OSPF database is consistent.\\n\\nImpact\\n- Single-host outage: host_1_1_1_1 cannot reach the gateway or servers (no L3 connectivity). It will fail DHCP renewal/contact and any external traffic.\\n- No broader network outage detected: servers (DNS, DHCP, web, load-balancer) and routing are functioning for the rest of the network.\\n\\nRelevant evidence excerpts (most relevant lines)\\n- host_1_1_1_1 ip/route:\\n  - inet 10.1.1.22/24 on eth0; default via 10.1.1.1\\n  - ip neigh (host): 10.1.1.1 dev eth0 FAILED\\n- ping from host to DHCP server:\\n  - From 10.1.1.22 icmp_seq=X Destination Host Unreachable (100% loss)\\n- router_dist_1_1 neighbor/fdb:\\n  - 10.1.1.22 dev br0 FAILED\\n  - bridge fdb includes owner MAC: c6:ac:f4:9b:df:b0 dev eth1 master br0\\n- switch_access_1_1_1 fdb:\\n  - c6:ac:f4:9b:df:b0 dev eth1 master br0 (host-facing port)\\n- router_core / OSPF routes:\\n  - router_core_1 shows 10.200.0.0/24 and other subnets in routing table via OSPF.\\n\\nConclusion / root-cause statement\\n- The network is largely healthy and OSPF/routed infrastructure is operating normally.\\n- The observed anomaly is a single-host L3 outage for host_1_1_1_1 (10.1.1.22). The immediate technical failure mode is ARP resolution failure between the distribution router and the host (both sides show neighbor state FAILED), despite the access switch having learned the host’s MAC. This indicates the problem is local to the host (host network stack, NIC, or host-side ARP/packet handling) or a host-specific software setting (ARP filtering/firewall), rather than a switch or core routing failure.\\n\\nIf you want, I can proceed to further targeted checks to disambiguate the root-cause hypotheses (for example: capture ARP/ICMP traffic on the host and switch port to see whether ARP requests arrive/are replied to; inspect host\\'s sysctl ARP/iptables/ebtables/arptables settings; attempt to ping host MAC from switch; temporarily move host to different switch port). (Note: you asked not to propose mitigations; I will only perform additional diagnostics if you request them.), please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='09662699-83fd-490d-aa20-fb714f6c9138'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5-mini", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
